  "_exec_summary": [
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000084672,
      "SummaryText": "The Bodega Bay Public Utility District (District) operates a wastewater treatment plant (Plant) in Bodega Bay, Sonoma County, California.  The District has implemented a federal Risk Management Plan (RMP) program as required under regulations of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).  Based on the regulatory requirements and on Facility operations, a Program Level 3 Prevention Program has been prepared for Plant operations.\r\n\r\nChlorine is used in the wastewater treatment process as a disinfectant.  Chlorine is stored in sufficient quantity to be regulated under RMP regulations.\r\n\r\nThis RMP includes a review of the potential hazards associated with chlorine, operational procedures, maintenance procedures, and employee training.  The District has prepared an Emergency Response Plan (ERP) that coordinates the actions of staff with local emergency responders.  This information has been provided to the Local Emergency Planning Committee and to local emergency response agencies.\r\n\r\nAs required under the RMP, in 2014 AMEC Environment and Infrastructure, Inc. (AMEC), and the District evaluated a worst-case release scenario using parameters described in 40 CFR Part 68.25.  The worst-case scenario is the rupture and release of the entire contents of a one-ton chlorine cylinder.  An alternative release scenario was evaluated using parameters described in 19 CCR 2750.4 and 40 CFR Part 68.28, based on off-site consequence guidance published by the EPA in 1999.  The alternative release scenario is a leak during cylinder change-out.  The Toxic Endpoint concentration (TE) for chlorine from the RMP regulations was used for this evaluation.\r\n\r\nIn 2020 Coastland Civil Engineers Inc., at the request of the District, prepared this update.  The development and population assumptions in the analysis prepared as part of the original RMP are still valid. This community has not seen significant growth in the past 5 years, and the study is still valid."
    }
  ]
